2) How I evaluated the two candidates, using common knowledge relevant to a CD listener:
- Back in Black (Classic Rock; Album-Oriented Rock): This is AC/DC’s 1980 album, widely regarded as an album-oriented rock record with tight sequencing, hard-driving guitar riffs, and strong, punchy production (produced by Mutt Lange). It is also one of the best-selling and most influential rock albums, so as a CD it represents a landmark studio album with notable production values and dynamic, high-energy performances that are well-suited to the CD format’s clarity and ability to present an album as an integrated listening experience.
- Simon and Garfunkel's Greatest Hits (Pop; Singer‑Songwriters): This is a compilation of their best-known folk-pop and singer-songwriter tracks (the duo is known for close vocal harmonies and acoustic-based arrangements). As a greatest-hits compilation it collects singles and standout tracks rather than presenting a single, cohesive studio album; the arrangements are often delicate and vocal-focused, which is a different listening experience from a full rock album.
3) Why I chose Back in Black and rejected Simon and Garfunkel's Greatest Hits:
- Choice rationale (Back in Black): Given that my stated interest is in listening to CDs (and, as a CD enthusiast, valuing what the format does best), I prioritize owning and listening to records that showcase a deliberately-crafted album experience and strong studio production. Back in Black is an album-oriented rock record with intentional sequencing, powerful electric-guitar tone, rhythmic drive, and high-production polish—qualities that benefit from the fidelity and continuity of a CD. Its status as a landmark, high-selling rock album also makes it an attractive CD to own and listen to as an exemplar of the format’s strengths.
- Reasons for rejecting Simon and Garfunkel's Greatest Hits: While Simon & Garfunkel’s music is excellent—classic songwriting, beautiful vocal harmonies and many widely loved singles—the release in question is a greatest-hits compilation. Compilations are great for sampling singles but do not offer the same cohesive album listening experience that I, as a CD enthusiast who values album presentation and production detail, am prioritizing here. Additionally, the more intimate, acoustic dynamics of their tracks, while wonderful, present a different type of listening focus (vocal blend and lyricism) rather than the full-band, high-energy production that highlights what many collectors appreciate on disc. For those reasons I select Back in Black as the better match to the CD-focused criteria I used.

